extended_text.content: Mullineux of Philadelphia was another of the artists who benefitted from the instruction of Blanche Lazzell in Provincetown. It is not recorded when these lessons took place, but Mullineux was active in the Philadelphia Print Club by 1930 and was a founding member of the American Color Print Society in 1939.

extended_text.content: Big Ten Co-Ed With Ski Mask No. 1 was shot at the University of Illinois, and is part of an iconic series for New Catalogue. In this series, young women modelling ski masks pose against the backdrops of Northwestern, Purdue University, and the University of Wisconsin, Madison, among others. New Catalogue's insertion of bizarre "stock" scenarios introduces a critique of the limitations of stock production companies as well as an expansion of their regular possibilities for wide material circulation.

46199.title: Blue Cat
46199.credit_line: Gift of Penny Ogle Weldon in memory of Jack Weldon
46199.inscription: signed and dated on cat's tail: Yoshio '96 ©

extended_text.content:
In this sculpture, the artist Yoshio Taylor refers to a famous Japanese ghost story in which a monk covers his body with sacred scripture to avoid possession by evil spirits. Taylor frequently makes nocturnal references, reflecting his preference for working late into the night, "when the subconscious comes through and you get interesting and inspiring images rushing through your head."

For the ghostly tale, search the Mount Royal College "gaslight etext" website for "The Story of Mimi-nashi-H?ichi" in Kwaidan: Stories of Strange Things by Lafcadio Hearn. [http://gaslight.mtroyal.ab.ca/ gaslight/]
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

8543.title: quilt; 'Stars & Eagle'
8543.creation_notes: Place of Creation= Northeastern United States
8543.description: Cotton, pieced and appliqued on cotton and embroidered with silk and cotton threads.
8543.credit_line: Orville A. and Elma D. Wilkinson Fund
8543.medium_support: cotton, appliquéd and quilted, cotton and silk embroidery
8543.provenance: (Cora Ginsberg, Inc. Tarrytown, New York); purchased by Indianapolis Museum of Art (June 19, 1975).
8543.inscription:
Embroidered, banner in central medallion: E. PLURIBUS UNUM
Embroidered, beneath banner in central medallion: 18 53
Embroidered, one state name on each star, clockwise from top center: Massachusetts / N Hampshire / N Jersey / S Carolina / Georgia / Connecticut / N York / Delaware / R Island / Maryland / N Carolina / Pennsylvania / Virginia

extended_text.content:
Patriotic themes and motifs have been incorporated into quilt designs since the Revolutionary War, 1775-1783. Union quilts, featuring the American eagle, were popular from the late 1780s until the 1840s and again during the Civil War. The design of this impressive quilt, dated 1853, was influenced by early nineteenth-century patriotic quilts and reflects the growing political tensions in antebellum America.

The quilt depicts a stylized central eagle, surrounded by a wreath of thirteen stars. From the eagle’s beak floats a streamer with the Latin mottom E Plubribus Unum, which means “one out of many”.

The eagle, the stars and the floral borders are appliquéd. The center of each pieced star is embroidered with the name of one of the thirteen original states: New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, New York, New Jersey, Delaware, Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, South Carolina and Georgia.
